<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-594  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 594.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Computer Graphics and Applications  March 1990 v10 n2 p20(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer graphics in medicine: guest editor's introduction.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rhodes, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer graphics researchers are naturally drawn to anatomicalpresentations and other medical imaging applications because ofthe wonder and exploration such applications invite.andP;  Computedtomography (CT) and magnetic resonance (MR) data have become sopopular among the general public that many believethree-dimensional computer graphics displays are a part of everyCT and MR exam when in fact they are not.andP;  It generally takes along time for graphics techniques to find their way into medicalapplications, due in part to the inattention of computer graphicsspecialists to such details as image accuracy, medical merit,clinical usefulness and cost effectiveness.andP;  Routine use ofthree-dimensional imaging systems in medical exams may becomestandard in the 1990s, but the systems should continue to beenhanced.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Imaging TechnologyThree-Dimensional GraphicsMedical DiagnosisResearch and DevelopmentComputer GraphicsPhysiological MonitoringEnhancementsIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>